<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Characteristic Species</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Forestiera</i> <i>pubescens</i>, <i>Rhus</i> <i>trilobata</i> and/or <i>Sambucus</i> <i>nigra</i> are dominant or co-dominant in the shrub canopy with <i>Atriplex</i> <i>canescens</i>, <i>Baccharis</i> <i>emoryi</i>, <i>Baccharis</i> <i>sergiloides</i>, <i>Ericameria</i> <i>linearifolia</i>, <i>Gutierrezia</i> <i>sarothrae</i>, <i>Phragmites</i> <i>australis</i>, <i>Prunus</i> <i>fasciculata</i>, <i>Salix</i> <i>exigua</i> and <i>Vitis</i> <i>girdiana</i>. Emergent trees may be present at low cover, including <i>Populus</i> <i>fremontii</i>, <i>Quercus</i> spp. or <i>Salix</i> <i>laevigata</i>. </div>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Vegetation Layers</h4>
	<div class="text">  Shrubs < 5 m; canopy is intermittent to continuous and may be two tiered. Herbaceous layer is sparse to intermittent. </div>
</div>

        
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Membership Rules</h4>
	<ul class="text">
		
		<li><i>Forestiera pubescens</i> > 50% relative cover in the shrub layer (Klein and Evens 2005, Buck-Diaz and Evens 2011, Evens et al. 2014).</li>
		
		<li><i>Rhus trilobata</i> > 50% relative cover in the shrub layer (Evens and San 2005, Keeler-Wolf et al. 1998, Klein and Evens 2005).</li>
		
		<li><i>Sambucus nigra</i> > 50% relative cover in the shrub canopy (Buck-Diaz et al. 2021).</li>
		
	</ul>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Habitats</h4>
	<div class="text"> Floodplains, stream banks, springs, river terraces, washes, swales, shallow valleys, or upland topography. Soils range from silty clays to coarse sands. The USFWS Wetland Inventory (1996 national list) recognizes <i>Forestiera pubescens</i> as a FAC plant and <i>Rhus trilobata</i> as a FACU plant. </div>
</div>

        
