<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Forestiera pubescens </i>is a long-lived, spreading shrub or small tree. Mature plants produce abundant crops of black drupes. Animals such as birds disperse the seeds. Plants form clonal thickets and sprout after stem damage (USDA-NRCS 2005b). The typical variety, var. <i>pubescens, </i>occurs in California and adjacent states; var. <i>glabrifolia </i>exists from New Mexico to Oklahoma. <br/>
<br/>
<i>Rhus trilobata </i>is an upright shrub to 2 m that forms large thickets. Roots are deep and branched extensively. Its woody, shallow rhizomes give rise to aerial stems that form clonal thickets. Leaves are deciduous with generally three leaflets. Fruits are red, hairy drupes. Shrubs produce long-lived seeds nearly every year. Birds and small mammals cache and disperse the seeds that collect in a seed bank. The seeds have dormancy broken by cold stratification. Seedlings are shade intolerant, and stems and rhizomes can live for more than 30 years (Nesom 2003). <br/>
<br/>
Leaf and stem characteristics in <i>Rhus trilobata </i>vary greatly, with up to four varieties that may be recognized in the state: the widespread var. <i>quinata </i>and var. <i>pilosissima; </i>var. <i>anisophylla </i>of the Mojave Desert; and var. <i>simplicifolia </i>(a CNPS list 2.3 plant). The <i>Jepson Manual </i>(Baldwin et al. 2012) does not recognize varieties, and vegetation surveys rarely do either. It and other recent taxonomic sources (Cronquist et al. 1997; Pell 2004) consider <i>R. trilobata </i>synonymous with <i>R. aromatica </i>of the eastern United States.  This species is an important basketry species for many southwestern tribes and like <i>Corylus cornuta, </i>may have been historically managed through fire and pruning (Anderson 2005).<br/>
<br/>
The <i>Forestiera pubescens </i>Shrubland Alliance has been expanded to include stands dominated or co-dominated by <i>Rhus trilobata</i> or <i>Sambucus nigra</i> (NatureServe 2015, Evens et al. 2014). Stands occur as scattered, small patches in California (McMinn 1939). They are not common and usually occur in slightly drier conditions upslope from flowing water in areas with subsurface moisture such as washes and river terraces, springs in hilly terrain, and narrows in desert canyon bottoms where moisture is forced to the surface. These stands are often associated with other riparian types dominated by <i>Baccharis salicifolia, B. sergiloides, Populus fremontii, Salix exigua, </i>and <i>Tamarix</i>. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
