    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast Ranges</b> (M262Ac-d, Ag, Aj-k). Stands of <i>Forestiera pubescens </i>occur locally in Contra Costa Co. including at Mt. Diablo, and they occur elsewhere south to the Temblor and Caliente Ranges (Twisselmann 1967).</li>
        
            <li><b>Great Valley</b> (262Ae). <i>Forestiera pubescens </i>grows at the Sutter Buttes, though stands remain unsampled.</li>
        
            <li><b>Mojave Desert</b> (322Ad, Ag-h, Aj-l, An). Stands exist in the eastern subsections around springs and in canyons (Thomas et al. 2004), and are found in Castle Mountains National Monument and Mojave National Preserve in the New York Mountains (Evens et al. 2014), and near Lancaster in the Antelope Valley (VegCamp and AIS 2013).</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada</b> (M261Er-s). Stands of <i>Forestiera pubescens </i>occur along Caliente Creek in the Tehachapi Mountains (Twisselman 1967) and along the base of the eastern escarpment in the Owens Valley as in the Alabama Hills.</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada Foothills</b> (M261Fa-e). Stands of <i>Forestiera pubescens </i>and <i>Rhus trilobata </i>may occur in the foothills of the Tehachapi Mountains, such as along Caliente Creek (VegCAMP 2015a). Stands of <i>Rhus trilobata </i>also occur scattered along foothill stream terraces generally, including in Butte Co. adjacent to <i>Quercus lobata</i> woodlands.</li>
        
            <li><b>Southeastern Great Basin</b> (341Fb-f). Stand density is high in the Argus, Coso, and Inyo Mountains (Thomas et al. 2004), especially at east-side canyon springs, some of which are foraging habitat for the endemic Inyo race of the California towhee (M. Bagley, pers. comm. 2000). Stands also occur in Death Valley National Park in the Panamint Mountains (Evens et al. 2014).</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Mountains and Valleys</b> (M262Bb-d, Bg, Bi-l, Bo-p). Occasional stands of <i>Forestiera pubescens</i> and <i>Rhus trilobata </i>occur around springs, seeps, washes, and river terraces in western Riverside Co., often adjacent to woodlands of the <i>Platanus racemosa, Quercus agrifolia,</i> and <i>Salix laevigata</i> alliances, including in the Perris Valley area on rocky, exposed upper slopes (Klein and Evens 2005). Stands in the Volcan Mountain area of San Diego Co. occur adjacent to dry meadows (Evens and San 2005). Stands also occur in swales and valleys adjacent to chaparral in the uplands of Anza-Borrego Desert State Park, such as in Ignacio Canyon (Keeler-Wolf et al. 1998b) and on the desert margins of the San Bernardino Mountains associated with stands of the <i>Baccharis emoryi - Baccharis sergiloides, Ericameria nauseosa,</i> and <i>Salix laevigata</i> alliances.</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> This semi-wetland alliance may be sensitive to invasion by <i>Tamarix</i>. We need to make efforts to protect stands of this alliance across its localized range in California. </div>
</div>

    

    

